Elixir leverages the Erlang VM, known for running low-latency,
distributed, and fault-tolerant systems. Elixir is successfully
used in web development, embedded software, data ingestion, and
multimedia processing, across a wide range of industries.
%
Elixir runs on the Erlang VM giving developers complete access
to Erlang's ecosystem. You can invoke any Erlang function inside
elixir with no runtime cost.
%
Feel free to interact with elixir developers, enthusiasts through:
Elixir Forum  → https://elixirforum.com
Github        → https://github.com/elixir-lang/elixir
IRC           → irc://irc.libera.chat/elixir
Twitter       → https://twitter.com/elixirlang
Slack         → https://elixir-slackin.herokuapp.com
Discord       → https://discord.gg/elixir
Stackoverflow → https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/elixir
%
Elixir REPL is called Interactive Elixir and abbreviated as IEx.
%
Mix is a build tool that ships with Elixir that provides tasks for
creating, compiling, testing your application, managing its
dependencies and much more.
%
To invoke an erlang function from within elixir, use the following
syntax:

    {colon}{erlang_module_name}{dot}{function_name}(params)

For example,

iex(2)> :crypto.strong_rand_bytes(8)
<<55, 72, 194, 212, 29, 112, 56, 195>>

Here, `:crypto` is the erlang module name and `strong_rand_bytes` is
the function name.

The same function in erlang shell is as follows:

2> crypto:strong_rand_bytes(8).
<<82,108,14,42,155,76,49,52>>
%
